<div1 type="trialAccount" id="t18650410-483">
               <interp inst="t18650410-483" type="uri" value="sessionsPapers/18650410"></interp>
               <interp inst="t18650410-483" type="date" value="18650410"></interp>
               <join result="criminalCharge" id="t18650410-483-charge-1" targOrder="Y" targets="def1-483-18650410 t18650410-483-offence-1 t18650410-483-verdict-1"></join>
               <join result="criminalCharge" id="t18650410-483-charge-2" targOrder="Y" targets="def2-483-18650410 t18650410-483-offence-1 t18650410-483-verdict-2"></join>
               <p>483. <persName id="def1-483-18650410" type="defendantName">
                     <interp inst="def1-483-18650410" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                     <interp inst="def1-483-18650410" type="age" value="20"></interp>
                     <interp inst="def1-483-18650410" type="surname" value="COOK"></interp>
                     <interp inst="def1-483-18650410" type="given" value="THOMAS"></interp>
                     <hi rend="largeCaps">THOMAS COOK</hi> (20)</persName>, and <persName id="def2-483-18650410" type="defendantName">
                     <interp inst="def2-483-18650410" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                     <interp inst="def2-483-18650410" type="age" value="20"></interp>
                     <interp inst="def2-483-18650410" type="surname" value="WALTERS"></interp>
                     <interp inst="def2-483-18650410" type="given" value="CHARLES"></interp>
                     <hi rend="largeCaps">CHARLES WALTERS</hi> (20)</persName>
                  <rs id="t18650410-483-offence-1" type="offenceDescription">
                     <interp inst="t18650410-483-offence-1" type="offenceCategory" value="breakingPeace"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18650410-483-offence-1" type="offenceSubcategory" value="wounding"></interp>, Felo<lb></lb>niously cutting and wounding <persName id="t18650410-name-625" type="victimName">
                        <interp inst="t18650410-name-625" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18650410-name-625" type="surname" value="DENNIS"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18650410-name-625" type="given" value="RICHARD HENRY"></interp>
                        <join result="offenceVictim" targOrder="Y" targets="t18650410-483-offence-1 t18650410-name-625"></join>Richard Henry Dennis</persName>, with intent to do him some grievous bodily harm.</rs>
               </p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">MR. DALEY</hi> 
                  <hi rend="italic">conducted the Prosecution, and</hi> 
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">MR. TAYLOR</hi> 
                  <hi rend="italic">defended Walters.</hi>
               </p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">
                     <persName id="t18650410-name-626" type="witnessName">
                        <interp inst="t18650410-name-626" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18650410-name-626" type="surname" value="DENNIS"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18650410-name-626" type="given" value="RICHARD HENRY"></interp>RICHARD HENRY DENNIS</persName>
                  </hi>. I am a sawyer, and live at Princes road, Plum<lb></lb>stead—on Monday evening, 20th March, I was in the Royal Oak, Plumstead, with my wife, my two daughters, and my little son—I went out at the back, and the two prisoners followed my son into the room and insulted my daugh<lb></lb>ters—Cook pulled them about, and tried to kiss them—Walters did nothing to my daughters; he tried to get Cook out—they were got out with the landlord's assistance—Cook then went to the bar, and accused my daughter of taking a watch—they were got out of the house twice, and about a quarter of an hour after that we left—I had the best part of a quart of ale in my hand, which was for supper—some one, I cannot say who, knocked me down, and then Cook knocked me down a second time—I got up, and was going up the road; Walters then turned round, knocked me down, knelt on me, and Cook stabbed me with a knife on the top of my head—I saw the blade shine—my little daughter came up and pushed them off—I got up, and was knocked down again by Walters—my son came up, and they ran away—with the second blow the knife closed—I am very weak still, and not able to work—I was also struck with the knife when it was half shut.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="italic">Cross-examined. Q.</hi> Had you had some drink? <hi rend="italic">A.</hi> A little—I was not more excited with drink than I am now; I had only had three pints and a half in the day—I had three parts of a quart in my hand, but that was spilt—I do not think I struck with the pot, but I might have, without being aware of it.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="italic">Cook.</hi>, I was asked to come into the parlour, and I sat between your wife and daughter—in a few miuutes I lost my watch—after that there was</p>
               <xptr type="pageFacsimile" doc="186504100191"></xptr>
               <p>some disturbance, and I went outside and struck some one on the head with A quar pot—I can't say who it was-you afterwards struck me on the Head with something—I put up my hand, and you nearly cut the top of my finger off with a knife, which you had in your hand. <hi rend="italic">Witness</hi>. I had no knife in my hand, but here is a wound on my finger from your knife—I may have kicked you when I was lying down, after I was knocked down—your finger was cut when your knife closed on your hand, when you stabbed me.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">JURY</hi>. <hi rend="italic">Q.</hi> Are these young men your daughters' acquaintance? <hi rend="italic">A.</hi> I do not think so; they have just come home from service, and I do not think they ever met the prisoners before—I have not seen the prisoners above six times—they have never been to my house, but have been past it.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">MR. DALEY</hi>. <hi rend="italic">Q.</hi> Had your wife or daughters been in the public-house before you came? <hi rend="italic">A.</hi> They were there when I arrived, at twenty minutes to 7.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">
                     <persName id="t18650410-name-627" type="witnessName">
                        <interp inst="t18650410-name-627" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18650410-name-627" type="surname" value="DAY"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18650410-name-627" type="given" value="EDWARD"></interp>EDWARD DAY</persName>
                  </hi>. I keep the Royal Oak—I was called to the bar by my daughter, in consequence of disgusting and obscene language by the prisoners, and found Cook pulling one of the young women about, and trying to kiss her—her father was rebuking him—he became very excitable towards the father, who I believe struck him—I slipped in between and told Cook he ought to be ashamed of himself for striking a man old enough to be his father—he became more violent, and I asked Walters to try to get him out—he made two attempts, but was unsuccessful—one of them, when he was got outside, jumped on the counter, and swore be would kill me.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="italic">Cook.</hi> I never jumped on the counter. <hi rend="italic">Witness</hi>. Ton did, and broke the glass; I bolted the door, and you broke it open and made a most foul oath that you would kill me—I know nothing about your watch.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">
                     <persName id="t18650410-name-628" type="witnessName">
                        <interp inst="t18650410-name-628" type="gender" value="female"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18650410-name-628" type="surname" value="DENNIS"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18650410-name-628" type="given" value="MARY ANN"></interp>MARY ANN DENNIS</persName>
                  </hi>. I am the prosecutor's daughter—I was with him on 20th March, and the prisoner followed my brother in out of the tap-room, and Cook took hold of me and kissed me; their discourse was not fit for any female to mention, and my father said he would not have it, and would not have us pulled about like that—Walters tried to get him out; he took him round the waist and said, "We have been mates all our life time, why should not we be mates now?"—Cook had a watch with a silver Albert to it—he put it in his left trouser's pocket, and went out of the room directly—he came in again, and said that he had lost his watch—my mother said to Mr. Day, "You ought to have a search as we have not been out of the room"—that was before he kissed me, and, before my father came—the landlord induced them to go, and I followed my father out—he had a quart-pot in his hand with some ale in it, which he was carrying home; directly he got outside the house he was knocked down; I cannot say who by—he got up again, and I saw the prisoners run off—I did not drink with either of them—I never saw them before.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="italic">Cross-examined, Q.</hi> Was there a good deal of quarrelling after you got outside? <hi rend="italic">A.</hi> Yes; I did not throw any broken earthenware, nor was any thrown—I stopped and picked up the quart pot, and some women pushed me down directly.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="italic">Cook. Q.</hi> Did not you drink with met? <hi rend="italic">A.</hi> No; nor did I put it to my month—I did not draw my chair close to you, and throw my clothes over your legs; that was my sister Martha.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">
                     <persName id="t18650410-name-629" type="witnessName">
                        <interp inst="t18650410-name-629" type="gender" value="female"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18650410-name-629" type="surname" value="DENNIS"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18650410-name-629" type="given" value="EMILY"></interp>EMILY DENNIS</persName>
                  </hi>. I was not at the beer-shop, but I saw the prisoners going along near our door, and my father after them—after they got round the corner, Cook began to knock my father about and got a knife,</p>
               <xptr type="pageFacsimile" doc="186504100192"></xptr>
               <p>and Walters laid his knees on my father while Cook struck him with the knife—I pulled Walters off my father; he pushed me, and called out for my brother—after that, one of the prisoners dashed my father up against the fence, and then they ran up the hill.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="italic">Cross-examined. Q.</hi> Did your father go by the door? <hi rend="italic">A.</hi> Yes; he did not come in—he went straight on the other side of the way, and these two men were on first—my father had nothing in his hand then; no quart<lb></lb>pot and no poker—I threw a <hi rend="italic">bit</hi> of china when I saw him on my father—they both threw my father down, and Walters held him down with his knees.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="italic">Cook. Q.</hi> Was not I by myself? <hi rend="italic">Q.</hi> No; Walters was with you; my brother and my father were not on top of you.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">
                     <persName id="t18650410-name-630" type="witnessName">
                        <interp inst="t18650410-name-630" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18650410-name-630" type="surname" value="DENNIS"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18650410-name-630" type="given" value="RICHARD"></interp>RICHARD DENNIS</persName>
                  </hi>. I am the prosecutor's son—on 20th March, he and my mother were drinking in the public-house—I went into the tap-room and asked Walters, who was there, to drink, which he did—I went to my father and mother, and went back—the prisoners came in, and I asked Walters whether he would come into the parlour, and sit with me—soon afterwards Cook insulted my sisters, and when I went back he said, "Are they your sisters?"—I said, "Yes, what is the matter?"—he said that he had lost his watch—Miss Day ordered him out of the parlour, and they went out—my father went out, and I found him lying down, and picked him up—when we got to Rutland-place, I saw my father knocked down again by Walters; he was cut, and bled very much—I took him home; Cook did nothing to my father; he was three or four yards away from him; the prisoners ran away.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="italic">Cross-examined. Q.</hi> Did not you see Walters trying to get Coot out of the public-house several times? <hi rend="italic">A.</hi> Yes, he took him round the waist; I did not see that Walters was bleeding, but there was a bason of blood and water when I went into their house to give them in charge—they both live in one house.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="italic">Cook. Q.</hi> Did I ask you to drink? <hi rend="italic">A.</hi> You asked Walters; you were excited with drink.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">
                     <persName id="t18650410-name-631" type="witnessName">
                        <interp inst="t18650410-name-631" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18650410-name-631" type="surname" value="MARSH"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18650410-name-631" type="given" value="EDWARD"></interp>EDWARD MARSH</persName>
                  </hi> (<hi rend="italic">Policeman, R</hi> 311). I took the prisoners; I found this knife (<hi rend="italic">produced</hi>), on Cook—it has stains of blood on it; Richard Dennis said that Cook had stabbed his father; Cook said, "Serve the old b——right"—Walters said, "You do not mean to put this on me, do you."</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="italic">Cook.</hi> The stain on my knife was from my handkerchief, which I had had on my head; I carry them together.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">
                     <persName id="t18650410-name-632" type="witnessName">
                        <interp inst="t18650410-name-632" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18650410-name-632" type="surname" value="LEWIS"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18650410-name-632" type="given" value="DUNCAN"></interp>DUNCAN LEWIS</persName>
                  </hi>. I am a medical practitioner; I was called in, and found Dennis partially bent double, as if from exhaustion, and literally deluged with external blood—the temporal artery was cut through; it would have cost him his life if it had not been cut through, as that caused it to contract—I considered him in danger; he was pulseless; I found several scratches on his head, and an incised wound on the summit; also, a deep incised wound measuring two inches from the margin of the ear to the angle of the jaw, so clear and deep that if I had not required to cut it, to take up the temporal artery, I could not have made a clearer incision—there appeared to be a degree of malignancy in the cut, for it had actually cut through a portion of the cartroied gland; such a knife as this would produce the wound.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="italic">Cross-examined. Q.</hi> Is it your opinion that the prosecutor had been drinking? <hi rend="italic">A.</hi> I cannot tell; the copious haemorrage must have a tendency to</p>
               <xptr type="pageFacsimile" doc="186504100193"></xptr>
               <p>sober even a drunken man—he answered every question I put to him in a rational manner, but seemed much excited.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="italic">Cook called the following witness.</hi>
               </p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">
                     <persName id="t18650410-name-633" type="witnessName">
                        <interp inst="t18650410-name-633" type="gender" value="female"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18650410-name-633" type="surname" value="MILLS"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18650410-name-633" type="given" value="ELIZA"></interp>ELIZA. MILLS</persName>
                  </hi>. I am Cook's landlady—I bathed his head when he came in; it was cut very much, and streaming with blood, and his finger was cut very badly—I cannot say whether his head was cut with a knife, or what, but as fast as I bathed ii the blood oozed out again—he also had a blow oil the face.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="italic">Cook.</hi> I am sure it was done with a knife, because it out half through my finger as well.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">COURT</hi>. <hi rend="italic">Q.</hi> Did you observe the cut on his finger? <hi rend="italic">A.</hi> Yes; it was very much swollen indeed, and cut too—whatever he touched he marked with blood—he knocked at the door and I let him in—the son, Richard, then rushed at the door—I put my hand out to prevent his coming in, and he pushed roe with great violence against the wall and rushed into the kitchen—the prisoners are very quiet respectable young men—they never keep late hours, or do anything I could complain off—they are plasterers.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="largeCaps">COOK</hi>.—
<rs id="t18650410-483-verdict-1" type="verdictDescription">
                     <interp inst="t18650410-483-verdict-1" type="verdictCategory" value="guilty"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18650410-483-verdict-1" type="verdictSubcategory" value="lesserOffence"></interp>
                     <hi rend="smallCaps">GUILTY</hi> 
                     <hi rend="italic">of unlawfully wounding. Recommended to mercy by the Jury, it being a tort of drunken quarrel.</hi>
                  </rs> 
                  <hi rend="italic">
                     <rs id="t18650410-483-punishment-124" type="punishmentDescription">
